==Overview==
{{Blurimage|file=Louisiana2.jpg|caption=The owl emitted a loud whistle, before going somewhere where the moon never shined.}}

The willow trees cover the land, weeping over the eternal night of the '''Louisiana Bayou'''. Their trunks stand long and solemn<span style="font-family:Calibri>—</span>but not proudly<span style="font-family:Calibri>—</span>with the drooping leaves covering almost all that you could call the sky. Looking up at the smoky heavens, a little white orb: the Moon luminates the lands of the carr. A deep sorrow paints the landform, sending one into a deep ocean of emotions, not a bright one. Owls screech in the distance, flying from branch to branch, roof to roof, looking down with such intent that can only be found in a loving mother.

Opaque water flows in large ponds, which form into rivers that flow into an ocean. Next to the waterline, trees stand weeping more than the willows. Their roots stretch deep into the unclean shallows, but it's not meant for them to absorb. They die out slowly, getting cut down by the rare storm. In their place a new tree pushes upwards, just for the cycle to continue. They would sink into the ground, sinking so far it becomes a part of the dirt, just short to a fossil.

Wood, stone, and other simple materials form many buildings. From the elements small shacks to big churches form, which if near water will stand close to sinking, and if on land become a landmark for navigation. The once fragile materials turn unbreakable once used for a structure. The insides may vary, but all share an intense coldness; both in design and temperature. The buildings form effigies of the buildings of the Louisianan bayou from [[The Frontrooms|home]], pulling wood and stone together for them.

{{Blurimage|file=WhoBuiltThem.jpg|caption=Who built them?}}

Scattered around are gravestones of different sizes<span style="font-family:Calibri>—</span>some small, some large. The graves have crosses, statues, or just a simple headstone on them, never clean, looking like they have been there for ages. They are almost purely decoration, only some have been found with actual caskets below them. The soil around it is always full of vegetation, which should suggest a body decaying into fertilizer, yet nothing was there, but an empty casket. The graves can appear far from water, indicating the existence of a nearby church. 

The land seems to have a strange hazard: it can take control of people, with the area holding voodoo dolls. Despite the trope, the practitioner has no malicious intentions, going as far as guiding the person to a safe spot or out of danger, but never to an exit; as if the practitioner wouldn't want them to leave. The sudden control can happen when near an egress, though even then the wanderer is still guided to shelter.

The safe zone the force moves them into is near a small statue which can only be called "effigies". Unrelated to the [[Object 21|object]]; they take the form of an uncanny statue of an angel statue, which can commonly be found in cemeteries. They are made of materials the land has an abundance of: stone, wood, clay, mud and even moss. Their poses can change, in a slow process, which could be compared to trees growing. One can be praying, one could be weeping. Other poses documented are: standing, slumped, pointing, kneeling and a pose with a ragged posture.
{{Blurimage|file=Level566 3.jpg|caption=I could feel the relief of leaving.|align=center|bg-size=1000px}}
==Beings==

The life of the Bayou isn't much different than what you would see in Louisiana. Beings mimicking crocodiles and snakes all exist, luring in the water. The non-level exclusives consist of worms-like entities: [[Entity 49|Pink Larvae]], [[Entity 78|Kavaroaches]] and [[Entity 190|Plastic Worms]].

==Fengator==
{{Entity Class|no=N/A|Hab=Bodies of water|Agg=4|Int=3|Dan=4}}
{{Blurimage|file=Fengator.jpg|caption=A float of fengators waiting for prey.}}
'''Fengators''' are the name provided for an alligator-like being that is commonly found in the '''Louisiana Bayou'''. Their appearance mimics real-world alligators, altough with a sharper snout and chubby feet. Their eyes glow a faint white, and floats of them infest the waters. Their snouts could be mistaken for rocks; they can stay still for hours, even weeks.

Their hunting pattern is highly unpredictable. They can shoot out of water to drag the misfortunate in, or go to land in the blink of a second. The attacks, despite being unpredictable, never feel random. A certain pull can be sensed, and rather than out of the danger, this time into the danger. This may suggest the Voodoo tries to pull people into it for food, <span style="font-family:Calibri>"</span>sacrificing<span style="font-family:Calibri>"</span> them. Not all the time, getting caught by one can certainly be beacuse of misfortune as well.

They cannot go past 5 meters once on land. If the five meters have an effigy in it, they will avoid the spot entirely even if prey is there. This could mean they are being controlled by the land as well, which could contradict the previously mentioned behavior of the practitioner of always doing what's best for the wanderer. Why would not going near an effigy be the best?

==Carr Snakes==
{{Entity Class|no=N/A|Hab=Bodies of water and land|Agg=4|Int=1|Dan=4}}
{{Blurimage|file=Carr Snake.jpg|caption=A Carr Snake on a porch.}} 

'''Carr Snakes''' are a unique snake-like specimen. The bottom of their body isn't any different from a snake, but the upper half is a millipede. Their movement is provided by the millipede legs, barely using the snake half. It almost seems like the snake is eating the millipede, while it can also look like the snake merges into the millipede. 

It uses the snake half to send a toxin to prey. This toxin is injected by the tail, and paralyzes the person. Once the person is paralyzed, the '''Carr Snake''' will go atop it and start devouring slowly. The meal is almost never finished, but the victim is left in a state which they can't live in. They only eat people at the verge of insanity, and in a state where it would be better to be dead.

When not hunting, they can be found eating the non-area specific lifeforms. They build small nests inside of the roots, out of grass and seaweed. They prefer to live near damp, overgrown structures, and similarly to the Fengators, they cannot go near effigies. They can sense when a person is being controlled, often following them and attacking during that time. If the attack is successful or not, the person will still retain injuries.

==White Owls==
{{Blurimage|file=White Owl.jpg|caption=White Owl looking down from a branch|align=center}}
<div style="background-color:rgba(62, 68, 60, 0.7); color: white; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:2px solid #705232; border-radius: 3px">
<br><center><span style="font-family:Georgia;font-size:15px;">
They stand close to the edge of the branch;

Their eyes staring down with maternal intents.

The owl's feathers seem to almost blanch,

Worsened by moonlight shone atop the willow, harshly sent.


The air grows thin beneath their watch,

Shadows hiding from their claws.

A benevolent being with mercy slipping away notch by notch;

Growing malevolent from the wrongs.


Guiding the lost back to their cradle,

Keeping the landscapes around stable.

"Why so tender?" one could ask;

A mother's love, claimed—never asked.


"Fear not my child" a faint whisper is heard;

Its angelic tone evoked a weird feeling.

"Did the statues become alive? They are still leaning."

But it was said by a white bird.


"We are not related by biology,

But who am I, besides a hopeless mother?

Although every life I touched became a part of my anthology.

Who will I be? A friend or another?


If a friend I will keep you close,

Never leaving below my control.

I am the practitioner, I do suppose,

The land has assigned me this role.


Becoming another would be much harder:

My eyes will never give you peace to offer. 

If your morals are low, consider yourself a martyr,

Your sacrifice to the root will not be in vain.


So what do you choose, dear {{USERNAME}}:

A friend or another?"
</span></center></div>

==Ingress & Egress<==

===Ingress===

*The land can be entered through entering a small chapel on [[Level 807|the forgotten swamp]], or on [[Level 822|the Lonely Valley]].
*Another means of entering is by entering what looks like a boathouse on [[Level 74|Australis]].

===Egress===

*The main egress follows a sequence of tasks. The exit can be found in a church which is located in the center of the '''Louisiana Bayou'''. You will know you entered the church once you smell holy water mixed with gold. The church is found submerged entirely, although stilts supporting it make it not sink. Once inside, blow all the candles out, and then noclip into the pedestal which will lead to [[Level 717|the Kings' Throne]]. If the candles aren't blown out the noclip will lead back to where you started. 
*Another exit is much simpler. It is said that many buildings that are not shacks or churches are Entrances to levels: hotels could lead to [[Level 5|the Terror Hotel]], indoor pools could lead to [[Level 30|the Waterpark]], malls could lead to [[Level 59|the Dark Mall]], etc. This exit is unstable and can commonly lead to [[The Void]].


















<div class="letter-frame"><div style="color:#000000"><small><small>09/30/1982</small></small>
Dear Cassidy,

I've been meaning to write this letter to you for years, I just never had such courage. So this [[Phenomenon 200|Sunny Night]] I dared to write it. You are the most amazing woman I have ever seen. You are brighter than the sun, and your heart is bigger than mine could ever be. 

In summary, you are the love of my life. Despite us having nothing united—besides having to live in the Wake—we could have so much more than that. 

So, meet me by the cliff under the tree. I will bring my guitar, and play a quick one.
<div style="text-align: right;">-Andrew
<small> ps. Even if you never come, I will remember the night.</small></div></div></div>
